1. Definition and Usage
- TypeError is thrown when an operation receives an argument of an unexpected type or attempts to perform an operation on a value of the wrong type (e.g., calling a non-function, accessing property on null/undefined).

2. Constructor and Instance Properties
- Constructor: TypeError(message?: string)
- Instance properties: name = 'TypeError', message string, stack via Error.prototype.stack when available
- TypeError inherits from Error and can be distinguished by instanceof TypeError

3. Examples and Catching Patterns
- Common uses: throw new TypeError('expected number') when input type invalid; catching via try/catch and checking instance: if (e instanceof TypeError) { ... }
- When to prefer TypeError: use when the argument type is wrong; for out-of-range numeric values prefer RangeError.

Supplementary Details

Technical specifications and implementation details
- Throwing pattern: throw new TypeError('message')
- Validation pattern: if (typeof x !== 'number') throw new TypeError('x must be a number')

